      {
        "annotationType": "ANNOTATION",
        "comment": {
          "commentType": "DOMAIN",
          "texts": [
            {
              "value": "The ATPase region is in the N-terminus, whereas the nuclease region is in the central part. The C-terminus is involved in prohead binding"
            }
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "annotationType": "ANNOTATION",
        "comment": {
          "commentType": "FUNCTION",
          "texts": [
            {
              "value": "The terminase large subunit acts as an ATP driven molecular motor necessary for viral DNA translocation into empty capsids and as an endonuclease that cuts the viral genome at a unique and precise dsDNA sequence to initiate and to end a packaging reaction. The terminase lies at a unique vertex of the procapsid and is composed of two subunits, a small terminase subunit involved in viral DNA recognition (packaging sequence), and a large terminase subunit possessing endonucleolytic and ATPase activities. Both terminase subunits heterooligomerize and are docked on the portal protein to form the packaging machine. The terminase large subunit exhibits endonuclease activity and cleaves the viral genome concatemer. Once the DNA is packaged, the terminase detaches from the portal and gets replaced by the tail to finish maturation of the virion"
            }
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "annotationType": "ANNOTATION",
        "comment": {
          "commentType": "SIMILARITY",
          "texts": [
            {
              "value": "Belongs to the Teseptimavirus large terminase family"
            }
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "annotationType": "ANNOTATION",
        "comment": {
          "commentType": "SUBUNIT",
          "texts": [
            {
              "value": "Homopentamer. Interacts with the terminase small subunit; the active complex is probably heterooligomeric. Interacts with the portal protein"
            }
          ]
        }
      },
